<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Slender and transparent body. Small head. Grasping spines abruptly curved. One row of stout teeth arranged in fan shape. One pair of lateral fins partially rayed, forward and equidistant from caudal septum. Lateral fins positioned at anterior end, at level of caudal septum with rayed lateral fins. Caudal fin damaged. Collarette and intestinal diverticula absent. No seminal vesicle visible.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
This species is found in the epipelagic zone (0-200 m depth) of the northern Indian Ocean (
<bibRefCitation author="Pierrot-Bults, AC" editor="Bone, Q" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Science Publications, New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="86 - 116" refId="B70" refString="Pierrot-Bults, AC, Nair, VR, 1991. Distribution patterns in Chaetognatha. In: Bone, Q, Kapp, H, Pierrot-Bults, AC, Eds., The Biology of the Chaetognaths. Oxford Science Publications, New York: 86 - 116" title="Distribution patterns in Chaetognatha." volumeTitle="The Biology of the Chaetognaths." year="1991">Pierrot-Bults and Nair 1991</bibRefCitation>
), the Gulf of Mexico (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/1538532" author="Pierce, EL" journalOrPublisher="The Biological Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="206 - 228" refId="B67" refString="Pierce, EL, 1951. The Chaetognatha of the west coast of Florida. The Biological Bulletin 100 (3): 206 - 228, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/1538532" title="The Chaetognatha of the west coast of Florida." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/1538532" volume="100" year="1951">Pierce 1951</bibRefCitation>
) and the Japanese coast (Tosa Bay, Sagami and Suruga) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02108551" author="Nagasawa, S" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Oceanographical Society of Japan" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="181 - 186" refId="B55" refString="Nagasawa, S, Marumo, R, 1972. Feeding of a pelagic chaetognath, Sagitta nagae Alvarino in Suruga Bay, central Japan. Journal of the Oceanographical Society of Japan 28 (5): 181 - 186, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02108551" title="Feeding of a pelagic chaetognath, Sagitta nagae Alvarino in Suruga Bay, central Japan." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02108551" volume="28" year="1972">Nagasawa and Marumo 1972</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" author="Ohnishi, T" journalOrPublisher="Plankton &amp; Benthos Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="176 - 187" refId="B59" refString="Ohnishi, T, Ueda, H, Kuroda, K, 2014. Community structure and spatial distribution of chaetognaths in Tosa Bay on the temperate Kuroshio coast of Japan. Plankton &amp; Benthos Research 9 (3): 176 - 187, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" title="Community structure and spatial distribution of chaetognaths in Tosa Bay on the temperate Kuroshio coast of Japan." url="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" volume="9" year="2014">Ohnishi et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
) and, in this study, it was found in the epipelagic zone (20-100 m depth) of the northern East China Sea (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Sampling stations in Korean waters. Empty circles, sampling stations; filled circles, the stations where the chaetognaths were secured." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.80184.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/704185" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">1</figureCitation>
: station nECS03).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
An inhabitant of the surface layer of the warm oceanic waters (
<bibRefCitation author="Tokioka, T" journalOrPublisher="Records of Oceanographic Works in Japan" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B86" refString="Tokioka, T, 1940. The chaetognath fauna of the waters of western Japan. Records of Oceanographic Works in Japan 12(22): e940." title="The chaetognath fauna of the waters of western Japan. Records of Oceanographic Works in Japan 12 (22): e 940." year="1940">Tokioka 1940</bibRefCitation>
). Mature specimen was reported to be 6-8 mm in length (
<bibRefCitation author="Alvarino, A" journalOrPublisher="University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B4" refString="Alvarino, A, 1967. The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959-1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4). University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" title="The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959 - 1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4)." year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Alvariño">Alvarino</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
). The temperature range in the sampling stations of this study was 18.49-28.84 °C and salinity range was 30.71-34.59 psu.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
Only immature individuals could be collected in this study. The specimens of 
<taxonomicName family="Pterosagittidae" genus="K." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="K. pacifica" order=" Aphragmophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="pacifica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">K. pacifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
we observed had one pair of fins and the structure of the fin was rayed, except for the base part close to the body. These were distinct characteristics of 
<taxonomicName family="Pterosagittidae" genus="K." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="K. pacifica" order=" Aphragmophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="pacifica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">K. pacifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that differentiated it from 
<taxonomicName family="Pterosagittidae" genus="K." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="K. subtilis" order=" Aphragmophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">K. subtilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Since seminal vesicles were not observed in all observed Korean specimens, they were classified as immature stage (
<bibRefCitation author="Alvarino, A" journalOrPublisher="University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B4" refString="Alvarino, A, 1967. The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959-1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4). University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" title="The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959 - 1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4)." year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Alvariño">Alvarino</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
